00:16:30.090 --> 00:16:31.800
We'll loop back through and
show you some of the things

00:16:31.800 --> 00:16:34.080
you can do with AppleScript.

00:16:34.650 --> 00:16:37.370
And for those of you new to AppleScript,
you want to find applications

00:16:37.370 --> 00:16:38.210
that have dictionaries.

00:16:38.260 --> 00:16:40.260
And the dictionaries will
tell you the kinds of things,

00:16:40.260 --> 00:16:45.410
the objects that you can interact with
in those applications with AppleScript.

00:16:45.700 --> 00:16:48.020
This is the dictionary
for Remote Desktop.

00:16:48.060 --> 00:16:51.730
And in it,
you see things like common tasks

00:16:51.840 --> 00:16:52.760
that you might want to run.

00:16:52.760 --> 00:16:57.680
Here's a list of the task
objects included with ARD.

00:16:57.680 --> 00:17:00.240
And we can do things
like send Unix commands.

00:17:00.300 --> 00:17:02.010
We can restart the machines.

00:17:02.080 --> 00:17:03.680
We can lock their screens.

00:17:03.680 --> 00:17:05.460
We can install packages.

00:17:05.620 --> 00:17:08.470
Let's take a look at a very
simple example of a task,

00:17:08.470 --> 00:17:10.180
the upgrade clients task.

00:17:10.230 --> 00:17:12.210
So you set up a bunch of
machines out of the box.

00:17:12.300 --> 00:17:14.940
They have the ARD 2.2
client installed on them.

00:17:14.940 --> 00:17:17.330
You've got
Apple Remote Desktop version 3.

00:17:17.340 --> 00:17:20.160
You want to upgrade all
of those clients to 3.0.

00:17:21.830 --> 00:17:22.890
We've got an Apple script.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:26.540
The very first line here is going to
create a variable called the clients.

00:17:26.560 --> 00:17:28.970
And in this variable,
we're going to stuff a list of all

00:17:28.970 --> 00:17:32.230
the computers that you have selected,
that you just selected

00:17:32.330 --> 00:17:34.040
in Apple Remote Desktop.

00:17:34.050 --> 00:17:36.790
And that'll remember those,
and then we'll create the task

00:17:37.110 --> 00:17:38.850
as a new upgrade client task.

00:17:39.010 --> 00:17:40.870
And finally...

00:17:42.780 --> 00:17:47.540
will execute that task on those clients.

00:17:47.690 --> 00:17:50.460
And because we're telling
Apple Remote Desktop to do something,

00:17:50.460 --> 00:17:53.780
we'll actually see those things
happen in the application as if

00:17:53.780 --> 00:17:58.350
we'd done those individual tasks
with our mouse and keyboard.

00:17:58.440 --> 00:18:02.860
A more involved example is
the send Unix task example.

00:18:02.860 --> 00:18:05.860
And in this case,
we want to run the Unix command uptime.

00:18:05.860 --> 00:18:09.310
We want to see how long these
computers have been running.

00:18:10.390 --> 00:18:12.630
Still very simple,
but we create a variable

00:18:12.690 --> 00:18:13.900
called myserverlist.

00:18:14.060 --> 00:18:17.180
And notice in this one,
instead of picking the machines that

00:18:17.180 --> 00:18:21.340
are selected in Apple Remote Desktop,
I've predefined an ARD list called

00:18:21.340 --> 00:18:25.000
servers to run this task on.

00:18:25.120 --> 00:18:26.340
And I created a new task.

00:18:26.420 --> 00:18:28.240
I called it anewtask.

00:18:28.350 --> 00:18:30.930
It's a sendunix command task,
but notice we have a lot of

00:18:31.130 --> 00:18:33.080
properties we can set for this task.

00:18:33.170 --> 00:18:36.930
These are options that you would
be clicking in the application if

00:18:36.930 --> 00:18:38.340
you were running them manually.

00:18:38.520 --> 00:18:41.500
Things like setting the name of the task.

00:18:41.560 --> 00:18:45.300
ARD will remember and show you the
currently running task or previous tasks.

00:18:45.570 --> 00:18:48.680
This one will be named
showComputerUptime.

00:18:48.850 --> 00:18:52.390
We can also decide when we
run this remote Unix task

00:18:52.570 --> 00:18:55.470
which user it will run as.

00:18:55.600 --> 00:18:59.540
And if you want to run a task that
requires administrative privileges,

00:18:59.590 --> 00:19:02.010
you want to choose the root user.

00:19:02.560 --> 00:19:06.020
The root user does not need to be
enabled on those remote systems.

00:19:06.060 --> 00:19:09.600
ARD will run your script
as root regardless.

00:19:09.860 --> 00:19:12.170
Finally,
there's ordinarily a checkbox in ARD to

00:19:12.240 --> 00:19:14.190
show the output of your Unix command.

00:19:14.190 --> 00:19:15.900
In this case,
this is something we want to see.

00:19:16.100 --> 00:19:20.290
And when this executes,
ARD will perform this task and

00:19:20.290 --> 00:19:22.810
show you the output within ARD.

00:19:23.190 --> 00:19:25.710
And finally,
the specific command that we're

00:19:25.720 --> 00:19:26.850
going to execute is uptime.

00:19:26.930 --> 00:19:30.580
It could be as involved
or as simple as you like.

00:19:31.970 --> 00:19:34.090
We're going to execute the
task that I defined on the

00:19:34.090 --> 00:19:36.760
machines in that computer list.

00:19:36.810 --> 00:19:38.470
But in addition to doing that,
we're going to create a

00:19:38.470 --> 00:19:42.060
variable called the result,
so that we can get those values back and

00:19:42.130 --> 00:19:44.630
maybe do something interesting with them.

00:19:45.910 --> 00:19:49.500
And this is what those results
look like in this case.

00:19:49.500 --> 00:19:53.880
A number of machines will
respond with their unique ID,

00:19:53.880 --> 00:19:57.250
their IP address,
and the results of that command.

00:20:00.650 --> 00:20:03.980
If you enter that script
within Script Editor,

00:20:03.980 --> 00:20:08.790
which is in--it's included with MacÂ OSÂ X,
you can save that as an application.

00:20:10.900 --> 00:20:12.030
And it resides in your finder.

00:20:12.030 --> 00:20:12.750
Double-click on it.

00:20:12.920 --> 00:20:16.580
You can also trigger it as a
result of things like mail rules.

00:20:16.610 --> 00:20:19.900
So let's say your boss sends
you an email message that says,

00:20:19.900 --> 00:20:22.140
I'd like to know what
the server uptime is.

00:20:22.180 --> 00:20:26.040
Your script can fire, get the uptime,
potentially mail it back to him,

00:20:26.040 --> 00:20:28.970
and he doesn't even need
to know you're not at work.

00:20:29.060 --> 00:20:33.470
And then we've also got iCalc capability.

00:20:33.470 --> 00:20:35.690
So if you want to schedule scripts
without using something like Cron--

00:20:36.190 --> 00:20:39.850
Just put them in your calendar,
set an alarm, and have that alarm

00:20:40.210 --> 00:20:42.410
trigger an AppleScript.

